Date: Fri 10 Jan 2003
From: Nick Honhold <nick@plewland.demon.co.uk>

A Comment in Response to "CJD (new var.) - UK: update 2003 (01)"
---------------------------------------------------------------
In January 2001 [see ProMED-mail post entitled "CJD (new var.) - UK: some
questions 20010109.0074"], I raised the issue of the increase in number of
sporadic Creutzfeldt-Jakob disease (CJD) cases in the UK from the early
90's and whether this might be related to Bovine spongiform encephalopathy
(BSE)/variant CJD [abbreviated as vCJD or CJD (new var.) in ProMED-mail].
It seems the specialist researchers have now found some evidence for this.
However, the good news is that there does seem to be a downturn in annual
cases of sporadic CJD in the UK (looked at annually and as rolling averages
for 2, 3, and 5 years). vCJD is also showing signs of having possibly
peaked, with decreases in case numbers in the last 2 years. Rolling
averages suggest either a plateau or a fall, and given the low numbers
involved, this more conservative measure is preferable. This year (2003)
may be the year when we can start to see with some confidence the trend in
the epidemic.
--
Nick Honhold
<nick@plewland.demon.co.uk>
[Most commentators regard the number of cases as still too small to allow a
reliable prediction in the absence of an accurate estimate of the average
incubation period. We can only hope that Nick Honhold is correct. - Mod.CP]
